					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wrongjohnsilver" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2000367); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2000367&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251590" alt="WrongJohnSilver" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2000367)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wrongjohnsilver" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2000367); return false;" >WrongJohnSilver</a></span> <span class="odate time_1476387211 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">13 Oct 2016 19:33</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2670209">
									

<p>Challenges are simply, &quot;Hey, writers, how about writing about this?&quot; The challenge for itself doesn't need to require much backstory.</p>
<p>For example, I've participated in two challenges so far. Mr. Wrong's Fill Up The Map Challenge asks people to find a country with no SCPs in it (as the <a href="/partial-worldwide-scp-map">Partial Worldwide SCP Map</a> shows) and place an SCP there. I've added <a href="/scp-2459">Pakistan</a> and <a href="/scp-2402">Bulgaria</a> to that list.</p>
<p>Then, there was Dexanote's challenge: tell a story about two SCPs fighting, as told from the point of view of a non-Foundation civilian. I wrote <a href="/funerals-are-fun">Funerals Are Fun</a>.</p>
<p>So, really, the challenge should set boundaries (but none that are too specific). The stories are what should come out of the challenge. As a result, most of the more interesting challenges are going to be set by people well aware of the community and the site content, in order to figure out what sort of challenge would be interesting to write, but, of course, there's no actual requirements to become a challenge proposer. When you've got the idea, present it. Hopefully, it's the articles that come out of the challenge that have that entertaining story.</p>
<p>Also, yeah, avoid writing SCPs on just a phone. It can be done, but having an honest-to-goodness keyboard in front of me helps a LOT.</p>

